# **ABSTRACT**

This thesis proposes and demonstrates that the Turin Shroud — the most examined and most venerated cloth in human history — was produced by Leonardo da Vinci between approximately 1476 and 1478 CE, during a documented period of biographical silence following the dismissal of charges against him in Florence, using an innovative combination of photothermal optical projection, silver nitrate surface chemistry, anatomical precision derived from direct dissection, and an inverted plaster relief contact process.

The argument is developed across eleven chapters, proceeding from simple arithmetic to complex systems analysis. Chapter Six establishes the foundational mathematical proof: the proportional dimensions of the Vitruvian Man (c.1490, Gallerie dell'Accademia, Venice), when multiplied by a scalar factor of 7.1 — derivable from Fibonacci compound proportion — produce the measured dimensions of the Turin Shroud cloth with a precision that cannot be attributed to coincidence. This mathematical relationship constitutes evidence of deliberate design that predates all currently proposed dates of production.

The thesis introduces an original analytical framework — the Canon of the Unseen — which identifies the structural law governing Leonardo's entire creative corpus: every major work contains two independently concealed devices that together produce a third unified state accessible only to the initiated viewer. The Shroud is demonstrated to be the supreme expression of this canon, simultaneously encoding a devotional object for the uninitiated and a complete scientific and mathematical argument about the relationship between divine proportion, human anatomy, and incarnate form.

Supporting evidence includes Leonardo's own authenticated writings — the Armenian letters documenting his physical presence in the eastern Mediterranean, the dated Madrid Codex I entries of 1493 and 1497, the Quranic citation in his private notebooks, and the Islamic arabesque emblem of his own Academy — convergently establishing both the geographic and intellectual context for the Shroud's production. The geological backgrounds of his paintings are demonstrated to constitute a travel diary encoding the specific landscapes of the Armenian Highlands and Taurus Mountains, consistent with the documented gap in his biographical record of 1476-1478.

The thesis addresses all major counterarguments in full, including the 1988 radiocarbon dating result, the STURP findings, the medieval provenance arguments, and alternative production hypotheses, demonstrating in each case either the technical inadequacy of the counterargument or its dependence on the 1988 corner-sample controversy now widely accepted as methodologically compromised.

The thesis concludes with a falsifiable scientific hypothesis: if Leonardo used his own blood in the second-layer application, as the evidence strongly suggests, his DNA will be recoverable from the Shroud blood zones. Cross-referencing against authenticated biological material from his confirmed remains at Amboise constitutes the definitive empirical test of the authorship claim.

*Keywords: Turin Shroud, Leonardo da Vinci, Vitruvian Man, Photothermal projection, Canon of the Unseen, 7.1 scalar ratio, Madrid Codex I, Armenian letters, Fibonacci proportion, Shroud authorship, Renaissance optics, Islamic geometric tradition.*

